# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: akutan-island
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Due to harsh winds, frequent cloud cover, and cold temperatures, vegetation is mostly tundra (grasses, mosses, berries, low-lying flowering plants) at lower elevations.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The highest point is Mount Moffett, near the northwest end of the island, at an elevation of 3,924 feet (1,196 m).
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] It is snow covered the greater part of the year.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The word *Adak* is from the Aleut word *adaq*, which means "father".
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak Island has been the home to Aleut peoples since antiquity.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Russian explorers in the 18th century also visited the island but made no permanent settlements.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] During World War II, the Imperial Japanese Army took control of two of the westernmost Aleutian Islands, Attu and Kiska, in the incorporated territory of Alaska, the first foreign enemy to occupy American soil since the War of 1812.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The Japanese also attacked the American base at Dutch Harbor by air.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The Japanese campaign coincided with the more well-known Battle of Midway.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] In response, the United States military began a campaign to oust the Japanese.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Since the nearest U.S. military presence was in Cold Bay, Alaska, the U.S. began to construct bases in the western Aleutian Islands from which to launch operations against the Japanese.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak Island was chosen as the site of an airfield, and flight operations began in September 1942.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] On May 11, 1943, four days after the initial invasion date was delayed by bad weather, American soldiers landed on Attu Island and defeated the Japanese garrison there, at the cost of 2,300 Japanese and 550 American lives.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Expecting a similar battle for Kiska Island, U.S. and Allied soldiers landing there August 15, 1943, found the occupiers had been stealthily evacuated by Japanese naval forces since the end of May, 1943.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Even so, over 313 Allied soldiers died from friendly fire, mines, and other anti-personnel devices during Allied operations to take back Kiska.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] In 1953, remains of 236 Japanese dead who had been buried in Adak Cemetery were reburied in Japan's Chidorigafuchi National Cemetery.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] After the war was over, some of the approximately 6,000 American military men who served on Adak during World War II recalled Adak's cold, foggy, windy weather; mud; Quonset huts; few women and no trees; and a volcano that from time to time would issue puffs of smoke.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak Naval Air Station continued to be a military base during the Cold War but was designated a Base Realignment and Closure (BRAC) site in 1995 and closed in March 1997.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Shortly thereafter, the town of Adak was incorporated at the site of the former base.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Down from a peak population of 6,000, the island recorded a 2020 census population of 171 residents, all in the city of Adak, in the northern part of the island.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] In 1980, the Aleutian Islands National Wildlife Refuge was created and much of Adak Island lies within its boundaries.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The Alaska Department of Fish and Game introduced approximately 23 caribou calves to the island in the late 1950s, in part to help prevent famine emergencies.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak Island, with its now large caribou herd of approximately 1,000 animals, according to a 2019 and 2022 count, has become a popular hunting destination.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak has a subpolar oceanic climate (Koppen Cfc), characterized by persistently overcast skies, moderated temperatures, high winds, significant precipitation and frequent cyclonic storms.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] At Adak, overcast conditions average nearly 75 percent of the time during June and July, dropping back to approximately 50 percent of the time from October through February.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak averages 173 days per year with fog.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The foggiest months are July and August, when an average of 26 of the 31 days have fog.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] This number drops dramatically toward the winter season, where the months of December through March have, on average, fewer than ten days with fog during any one month.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Gales occur in all months of the year at Adak, with the greatest chances being from December through March.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] A peak gust of 109 knots (202 km/h; 125 mph) occurred at Adak in March 1954.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak's average temperatures range from 20 to 60 °F (−7 to 16 °C), with a record high of 75 °F (24 °C) in August 1956 and a record low of 3 °F (−16 °C) in January 1963 and February 1964.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Average annual precipitation is about 54.8 inches (1,390 mm).
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] October to January are the wettest months due to especially frequent and intense mid-latitude cyclonic storms, while May to July represent markedly drier months; thunderstorms, common in mid-latitude continental areas, are virtually unknown here.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] November is the average wettest month, while July is the average driest month.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Average snowfall is 100 inches (2,500 mm), falling primarily on the upper reaches of the volcanoes.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak has an average of 341 days per year with measurable precipitation.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak is served by the Aleutian Region Schools.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The Adak School, now closed due to declining enrollment, used to serve grades K–12 and had around 20 students before it was officially shuttered on June 30, 2023.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] A land exchange between Alaska Native Regional Corporations, the U.S.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Navy, and the Department of the Interior has transferred most of the naval facilities to the Aleut Corp.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] A portion of the Island will remain within the National Maritime National Wildlife Refuge, managed by U.S.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak currently provides a fueling port and crew transfer facility for foreign fishing fleets—an airport, docks, housing facilities and food services are available.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] A grocery and ship supply store and restaurant opened in February 1999.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Aleut Corporation maintains the facilities.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Contractors are performing an environmental clean-up.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Alaskan-owned Norquest-Adak Seafood Co. processes Pacific cod, pollock, mackerel, halibut, albacore and brown king crab.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Four residents hold a commercial fishing permit, primarily for groundfish.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] In 2022, Netflix aired a docuseries about explorers seeking pirate gold on the island.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Because of its naval aviation past, Adak has an unusually large and sophisticated airport for the Aleutian Islands.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The Adak Airport is operated by the State of Alaska Department of Transportation.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak Airport has a control tower, an Instrument Landing System and two runways; 7,790 ft (2,370 m) and 7,605 ft (2,318 m) respectively.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Both runways are asphalt paved, 200 ft (61 m) wide and at an elevation of 19 ft (6 m).
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Alaska Airlines operates twice-weekly Boeing 737-800 passenger and cargo jet service from Anchorage.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] At present, flights operate each Wednesday and Saturday (weather permitting).
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Occasionally, extra seasonal flights are operated to meet the demand of the fishing season.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak Airport was historically served for many years by Reeve Aleutian Airways (RAA), with scheduled passenger flights to Anchorage operated with Lockheed L-188 Electra turboprop combi aircraft during the 1970s, followed by Boeing 727-100 jet combi aircraft during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Other facilities in Adak include three deep water docks and fueling facilities.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] There are approximately 16 miles (26 km) of paved and primitive roads on Adak, all privately owned by the Aleut Corporation.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The Aleutian shield fern is an endangered species found only on this island.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adak National Forest is a small copse on the island jokingly referred to as a national forest.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] Adagdak and Mount Moffett volcanoes are located on Adak.
[src:akutan-island/adak-island] The igneous rock type adakite is named after Adak.
[src:akutan-island/adugak-island] The name was recorded in 1840 by Ivan Veniaminov.
[src:akutan-island/adugak-island] It may arise from the word "Adudak", which means "somewhat long".
[src:akutan-island/adugak-island] The island about 1.2 miles (2 km) long and is located 5.0 miles (8 km) off the northwest coast of Umnak Island.
[src:akutan-island/adugak-island] It reaches an elevation of about 102 feet (31 m) above sea level and the area around the island is extremely hazardous to ships because of the numerous rocks that lie just below the surface of the water.
[src:akutan-island/adugak-island] The island has been protected as a rookery for the endangered Steller sea lion, which has been observed during the winter feeding on the fish that inhabit the water nearby.
[src:akutan-island/adugak-island] Cassin's auklet once lived in the area, but disappeared.
[src:akutan-island/adugak-island] They also disappeared from other Aleutian islands such as Keegaloo, and Ilak Island due to introduced predators, oil spills, and mortality from fisheries interactions.
[src:akutan-island/adugak-island] Some animals on the island were tested positive for Polydnavirus, along with Yunaska.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Agattu has been recognised as an Important Bird Area (IBA) by BirdLife International.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] It has seven large seabird colonies, and an estimated population of 66,000 birds.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] About 1% of the global population of red-faced cormorants and tufted puffins nest on the island.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Other inhabitants include rock sandpiper, red-necked phalarope, grey-crowned rosy finch and snow bunting.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Aleutian cackling geese were reintroduced to the island after foxes were eliminated from the island in the 1970s.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] The elimination of the foxes on the island also made it possible for conservationists to reintroduce the Evermann's rock ptarmigan (*Lagopus muta evermanni*).
[src:akutan-island/agattu] In 2006 there were reports of at least 25 breeding pairs of the ptarmigan on the island.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Agattu is unique among the volcanic Aleutian Islands in being composed almost entirely of well-bedded sedimentary rocks.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] These rocks were clearly deposited in water and are composed chiefly of amorphous silica and fine detritus derived from a volcanic terrain.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Igneous rocks are sparsely represented by intrusions of porphyry, diabase, and trap.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] The entire island has been heavily glaciated.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Archeological excavations have discovered evidence and remains of Aleuts living on Agattu Island as early as 760 BCE.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Based on the number of simultaneously inhabited archeological sites on the island, experts have estimated that the pre-contact population may have reached 500–1000 individuals.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] After Russian contact with the Aleutians in 1751, the population on Agattu declined precipitously.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Russian traders would stay multiple years at a time in the Near islands hunting sea otter.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] Interactions with the Aleuts were sometimes violent.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] A veteran Russian navigator was killed by the locals on Agattu in 1761.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] By the 1760s, all Near Islanders had moved into a single village on Attu Island.
[src:akutan-island/agattu] During World War II, the villagers of Attu were interned in Japan and at war's end the survivors were resettled on Atka Island.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] The island lies east of Akutan Island and southwest of Unimak Island, across the Unimak Pass strait.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] The Krenitzin Islands lie to the south and southeast, across the Avatanak Strait.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] Akun Island has a land area of 64.39 sq mi (166.77 km²).
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] It is unpopulated, except for airport workers and a few people controlling the cattle.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] Akun Island is home to a small but significant population of cows.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] They are no longer domesticated but the population is controlled.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] Three domesticated horses also inhabit the island.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] With the cessation of amphibious airplane service to Akutan on Akutan Island, the Akutan Seaplane Base closed in 2012.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] It was replaced by a new $75.5m land-based airstrip six miles (9.7 km) across the water on Akun Island, named Akutan Airport.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] It was built by Kiewit, R&M Consultants, and DOT.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] The airport was connected to Akutan by an expensive hovercraft shuttle, which couldn't operate safely when winds were too strong or waves too high.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] A helicopter provides the link between Akun and Akutan.
[src:akutan-island/akun-island] The airport has a small hotel, which is used when a flight arrives and the hovercraft is unable to run.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Akutan is located in the Aleutian Islands Recording District.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Akutan is located on Akutan Island in the eastern Aleutians, one of the Krenitzin Islands in the Fox Islands group.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] It is 35 miles (56 km) east of Unalaska, and 766 miles (1,233 km) southwest of Anchorage.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Akutan lies in the maritime climate zone, resulting in mild winters and cool summers.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Mean temperatures range from 22 to 55 °F (−6 to 13 °C), and precipitation averages 28 inches (710 mm) per year.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] High winds and storms are frequent in the winter, and fog is common in the summer.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 18.9 square miles (49 km2), of which, 14.0 square miles (36 km2) of it is land and 4.9 square miles (13 km2) of it (25.69%) is water.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Akutan began in 1878 as a fur storage and trading port for the Western Fur & Trading Company.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The company's agent established a commercial cod fishing and processing business that quickly attracted nearby Unangan to the community.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] A Russian Orthodox church and a school were built in 1878, but was replaced by the St.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The Pacific Whaling Company built a whale processing station across the bay from Akutan in 1912.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] It was the only whaling station in the Aleutians, and operated until 1939.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] After the Japanese attacked Unalaska in June 1942, the U.S. government evacuated Akutan residents to the Ketchikan area.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] In June 1942, a Japanese A6M Zero fighter piloted by Tadayoshi Koga crashed on Akutan Island.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] It was recovered in July by the United States Army Air Force.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] This plane, dubbed the Akutan Zero, significantly aided American tacticians in devising dog fighting techniques to defeat the Zero, and helped change the course of the war.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The village was re-established in 1944, although many villagers chose not to return.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] This exposure to the outside world brought many changes to the traditional lifestyle and attitudes of the community.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] A federally recognized tribe is located in the community—the Native Village of Akutan.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The population of the community consists of 16.4% Alaska Native or part Native.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Akutan is a fishing community, and is the site of a traditional Unangan village.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Approximately 75 persons are year-round residents; the majority of the population are transient fish processing workers that live in group quarters.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Census as an unincorporated Aleut village.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] It reported 65 residents, of whom 63 were Aleut and 2 were White.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] In 1890, it reported 80 residents, of whom 71 were Native, 6 were Creole (Mixed Russian & Native) and 3 were White.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] It did not appear again until the 1920 census.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Beginning in 1990, it reported an Asian plurality of residents.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] It is one of only three communities in Alaska as of 2010 to have either an Asian plurality (Kodiak) or majority (Adak).
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] As of the 2020 census, Akutan had a population of 1,589.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] 1.4% of residents were under the age of 18 and 5.5% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] For every 100 females there were 309.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 313.5 males age 18 and over.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] 0.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 100.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] There were 48 households in Akutan, of which 39.6% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Of all households, 33.3% were married-couple households, 39.6% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 20.8% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] About 27.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] There were 52 housing units, of which 7.7% were vacant.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 0.0%.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] As of the census of 2000, there were 713 people, 34 households, and 17 families residing in the city.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The population density was 50.8 inhabitants per square mile (19.6/km2).
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] There were 38 housing units at an average density of 2.7 units per square mile (1.0 units/km2).
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The racial makeup of the city was 23.56% White, 2.10% Black or African American, 15.71% Native American, 38.57% Asian, 0.28% Pacific Islander, 18.23% from other races, and 1.54% from two or more races.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] 20.76% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] There were 34 households, out of which 20.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 32.4% were married couples living together, 14.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 47.1% were non-families.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] 38.2% of all households were made up of individuals, and 2.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The average household size was 2.21 and the average family size was 3.00.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] In the city, the age distribution of the population shows 3.1% under the age of 18, 11.1% from 18 to 24, 48.2% from 25 to 44, 36.2% from 45 to 64, and 1.4% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] For every 100 females, there were 334.8 males.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 342.9 males.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The median income for a household in the city was $33,750, and the median income for a family was $43,125.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Males had a median income of $13,988 versus $23,750 for females.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The per capita income for the city was $12,258.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] None of the families and 45.5% of the population were living below the poverty line, including no under eighteens and 40.0% of those over 64.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Census, total housing units numbered 38, and vacant housing units numbered 4.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The unemployment rate at that time was 83.89 percent, although 84.84 percent of all adults were not in the work force.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Water is supplied by a local stream and dam, originally constructed in 1927.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Water is treated and piped into all homes.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Funds have been requested to develop two new water catchment dams, and construct a new 125,000-gal. water storage tank and treatment plant.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Sewage is piped to a community septic tank, with effluent discharge through an ocean outfall.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Refuse is collected three times a week; a new landfill site and incinerator were recently completed.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Trident Seafoods operates its own water, sewer and electric facilities.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Electricity is provided by Akutan Electric Utility.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] There is one school located in the community, Akutan School of the Aleutians East Borough School District (AEBSD), attended by 18 students.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Circa October 1978 the school, then a part of the Aleutian Region School District, had a single teacher, and 12 students.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Local hospitals or health clinics include Anesia Kudrin Memorial Clinic.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Anesia Kudrin Memorial Clinic is a Primary Health Care facility.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Eastern Aleutian Tribes Inc. operates the Anesia Kudrin clinic as part of its health care system.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The clinic is a qualified Emergency Care Center.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Akutan is classified as an isolated town/Sub-Regional Center, it is found in EMS Region 2H in the Aleutian/Pribilof Region.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Emergency Services have coastal and helicopter access.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Emergency service is provided by volunteers and a health aide.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] There is a physician assistant certified at the Anesia Kudrin clinic, and for much of the year there a physician assistant or nurse practitioner at the processing plant's occupational medicine/urgent care clinic.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Auxiliary health care is provided by Akutan First Responders; or by flight to Unalaska or Anchorage.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Transportation is provided by seaplane, by private or fleet fishing vessels, and the State Ferry makes monthly visits in summer weather.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Commercial fish processing dominates Akutan's cash-based economy, and not many locals are seasonally employed.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Trident Seafoods operates a large processing plant west of the city for cod, crab, pollock and fish meal.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The population of Akutan can quadruple or quintuple during processing months.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Seven residents hold commercial fishing permits, primarily for halibut and other groundfish.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Subsistence foods include seal, salmon, herring, halibut, clams, wild cattle, and game birds.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Boats and amphibious aircraft, hovercraft, or helicopter are the only means of transportation into and out of Akutan.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] A 200-foot (61 m) dock and a small boat mooring basin are available.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Plans are underway to develop a practical way to get to a large boat harbor that has been built at the head of the bay.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The State Ferry operates from Kodiak bi-monthly between May and October.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Cargo is delivered weekly by freighter from Seattle; the City owns and operates a landing craft, the M/V Akutan.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Akutan has no airstrip due to the steep terrain, however, a seaplane base is available and open to the public.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Helicopter service between Akutan and Akun Island, the location of Akutan Airport, began in February 2014.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The only airline company serving the airport is Grant Aviation, flying to nearby Dutch Harbor.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] The airport was expected to cost $77 million of which nearly $60 million came from the U.S. federal government.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-alaska] Trident paid $1 million towards the cost of the airport.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-hot-springs] The Akutan geothermal area is located in the Aleutian Islands; the hot springs are scattered across multiple locations.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-hot-springs] They discharge into the bay from various local streams and groundwater.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-hot-springs] Akutan Peak is a stratovolcano with a summit caldera.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-hot-springs] The active hot springs are located at the head of the valley and the shore of Hot Springs Bay.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-hot-springs] There are five groupings of geothermal springs in the lower Hot Springs Bay Valley (HSBV) geothermal area.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-hot-springs] The water emerges from the springs at 77 °C (171 °F) and discharges into Hot Springs Creek and other streams.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-hot-springs] The geothermally heated water emerges from beach sands, fissures in hydrothermally cemented stream bank sediments, from pools in the alluvium and directly into the creek.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] The island is approximately 18 mi (30 km) in length.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] Mount Akutan volcano is located on the island, which had a major lava eruption in 1979.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] The island's population was 1,027 (2010 census).
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] All lived in the city of Akutan, near the island's eastern end.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] A significant geothermal area is located on the island including the Akutan Hot Springs.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] Akutan is an Aleut name reported by Capt.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] Pyotr Krenitsyn and Mikhail Levashev in 1768, and spelled Acootan by James Cook in 1778.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] This name may be from the Aleut word "hakuta" which, according to R.
[src:akutan-island/akutan-island] The Akutan Zero, a Japanese Zero, was named for the island after it crashed there during World War II and was recovered by the United States military.
